Fired when an IP has been deemed malicious by Okta. This event fires only when an organization has configured their Okta ThreatInsight security settings to monitor auth attempts OR monitor auth attempts and block malicious IPs. This can be used to see details about the IPs Okta has deemed malicious, including the type of security threat (eg: Brute Force, Password Spray) and the resulting action. When fired, this event contains information about the type of security threat detected, the IP, and the result of the detection. The result of this event is determined by the security settings configured - if an organization has configured Okta to monitor authorization attempts, then the result will be 'ALLOW'; if an organization has configured Okta ThreatInsight security settings to monitor authorization attempts and block malicious IPs then the result will be 'DENY'. Related events include: In the case of 'monitor only' (versus monitor and block), when this event fires, the debug context for the related user.auth or user.session event will contain information about the detected threat.

Fired when an IP has been deemed malicious by Okta. This event fires only when an organization has configured their Okta ThreatInsight security settings to monitor auth attempts OR monitor auth attempts and block malicious IPs. This can be used to see details about the IPs Okta has deemed malicious, including the type of security threat (eg: Brute Force, Password Spray) and the resulting action. When fired, this event contains information about the type of security threat detected, the IP, and the result of the detection. The result of this event is determined by the security settings configured - if an organization has configured Okta to monitor authorization attempts, then the result will be 'ALLOW'; if an organization has configured Okta ThreatInsight security settings to monitor authorization attempts and block malicious IPs then the result will be 'DENY'. Related events include: In the case of 'monitor only' (versus monitor and block), when this event fires, the debug context for the related user.auth or user.session event will contain information about the detected threat.
